    <h1>How to make a 404 page (& other things to do with .htaccess)</h1>
    <h4>.htaccess is a cool format</h4>
    .htaccess is one of the main formats used in web development, so it's very important that you know how to use it. 
    It <italic>basically</italic> just uses plaintext, but there are a few rules. 
    <ol>
        <li>The rules in the file apply to the current and sub directories.</li>
        <li>The file can only be name '.htaccess'. ONLY '.htaccess'. Nothing else.</li>
    </ol>
    Now, to make an error page, you need to write: <code_snippet>ErrorDocument 404 /[name of 404 page].html</code_snippet>.
    <br><br>
    Yep. That's it.<br><br>
    Anyway, there are other things you can do with .htaccess. <br>
    <italic>Let's go through them.</italic>
    <ul>
        <li>Handle any error by typing a different error code into the space after ErrorDocument. Example: <code_snippet>ErrorDocument 503 /[name of 503 page].html.</code_snippet></li> A list of error codes can be found <href>
    </ul>
    <br><br><br>
